                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3492.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at Chihuahua</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Chihuahua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-03T22:00:00-07:04">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 3, 1912—10 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> (Received, via El Paso, Tex., April 4, 1912—7.40 p.m.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>New regulation by the military authorities requires passports all persons leaving
                    city. On account censorship my last cipher telegram to the Department was kept
                    by the military authorities an hour before forwarding; another a few days since
                    several hours. Protests seem unavailing.</p>
                <p>Money-order service in State discontinued a month ago. Postmaster suggests
                    general warning against the issue of international orders payable here.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Letcher.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
